n into American life. Berman investigates a wide range of sources-radio and television broadcasts, bestselling books, sociological studies, debates about Jewish marriage and intermarriage, Jewish missionary work, and more-to reveal how rabbis, intellectuals, and others created a seemingly endless array of explanations about why Jews were indispensable to American life. Even as the content of these explanations developed and shifted over time, the very project of self-explanation would become a core element of Jewishness in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aJewish leadershipxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aJewish leadershipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxIdentityxUnited States. 0aJewsxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aJewszUnited StatesxIdentity. 0aJewszUnited StatesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aJudaism and the social sciences. 0aReligion and sociologyxUnited States. 0aReligion and sociologyzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943704423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520943704.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles